    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so it's basically just the sugar and protein reacting. what actually happens at a molecular level during that \"dance\" though? like how do they actually transform into those new flavor compounds?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "At the molecular level, the Maillard reaction is a cascade of reactions, not just a single event. It starts when the carbonyl group of the reducing sugar reacts with the free amino group of an amino acid. This initial condensation forms a glycosylamine, which then rapidly rearranges into an Amadori product. This Amadori product is the starting point for the whole flavor explosion, which, as the heat continues to climb, breaks down through various intermediate steps—like fragmentation, dehydration, and Strecker degradation—to produce hundreds of different volatile compounds. These final products are what give us those savory, nutty, and roasted aromas.",
      "source": "target",
